where ,  (, ) are the curvature and
metric defined by  () (The additional terms
in the bracket involving derivatives of the scalars , 
are 

) .

When , the  dimensional action simplifies
into the sum of the 4D Hilbert Einstein action plus an action for
the scalar field = , which determines the size
of extra dimensions. The line element  is now the
metric in 4D Einstein frame.

The second term in () acts as a scalar field potential for



V = - _n
e^-(n+2) .
Therefore in order to have a positive potential we need
to compactify a space with negative curvature.  For extra
dimensions of constant curvature, that is spherical or hyperbolic
spaces, we see from () that the potential has an
exponential form. (For the flat case the potential vanishes.)

Except for very large , the parameters in the theory are all of
order  which is a problem in generating inflation from the
potential in (). To have large acceleration, we need large
, but this also implies large slope  and so
the kinetic energy quickly catches up according to the equation of
motion for . Therefore the number of e-foldings of such
inflationary models is expected to be only of order . This is
indeed the case for compactification on a single hyperbolic space
. If we generalize this setup to extra dimensions which
are product spaces for example, this problem might be evaded
because there are more scalars and more complicated potentials.
The situation might be similar to the hybrid model of inflation.
We construct a model in Sec.  showing that sufficient
inflation can be achieved even if all parameters are of order .

The plan of the paper is as follows. In Sec. , we give a
general formulation of Einstein gravity in vacuum for product
spaces of flat, spherical and hyperbolic spaces. In
Sec. , we begin with a review of compactifications on a
single hyperbolic space , and then analyze the
next simplest case, a product of two compact spaces
.  Although we did not find
sufficient inflation for these cases, but we show in
Sec.  that in principle, similar models with only
coefficients of order one can produce eternal inflation. In
Sec.  we begin analysis of general product spaces
, where the large  dimensions
does not have to be flat and  does not have to be . We have
found exact solutions for the case , where
 can be a spherical, hyperbolic or flat space. Finally we
comment on our results in Sec. .


Generic case  
In this section we consider Einstein gravity in vacuum for
spacetimes which are products of an arbitrary number of spaces,
which are each either flat, spherical or hyperbolic.  In Subsec.
 we first give the vacuum Einstein equations, and then
treating the scale factors as scalar fields we rewrite the theory
from the dimensionally reduced viewpoint in Subsec. . The
advantage of this approach is that we can now apply our knowledge
of scalar field inflation.

